  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects students and professionals alike, especially those from underrepresented groups. Growing up in Kansas City, I've seen how stereotypes about math and science can make kids feel like they're 'not good enough' before they even start school. My parents only went to primary school, so they never had the same exposure to advanced STEM fields as someone who grew up in a family of engineers or scientists. That gap in experience can make it harder for kids from similar backgrounds to see themselves in STEM careers. I've also noticed how social media amplifies these issues—people online often share stories about failing in math or feeling intimidated by coding, which can create a self-fulfilling prophecy. As someone who's creative but not particularly strong in technical fields, I understand how stereotype threat can make someone doubt their abilities even when they're capable. The key to addressing this isn't just changing policies but creating spaces where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. For example, in my job as a waiter, I've seen how small talk about hobbies and interests can help build trust and reduce anxiety. If we could create more inclusive environments where people feel seen and valued for who they are, not just what they're good at, stereotype threat would become less of a problem. It's not about fixing STEM education—it's about making sure everyone has the chance to thrive in it.",
